{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Ewmi2j7UdWxsSTk9vbWbXm","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Issue #811: Should `score()`/`apply_metrics()` return warning about failed metrics in a batch?\n     2→\n     3→## Source\n     4→\n     5→- **GitHub**: https://github.com/epiforecasts/scoringutils/issues/811\n     6→- **Action Summary**: Modify `apply_metrics()`/`run_safely()` to collect error messages in a list during the `lapply` loop, then emit a single batched `cli_warn()` summarizing all failed metrics at the end. Update test expectations in `test-score.R`.\n     7→- **Status Note**: Still relevant. `run_safely()` in `R/score.R:210` uses `try()` + immediate `cli_warn()` per failed metric. No batching/deferring mechanism exists. Failed metrics silently dropped from `scores` object via `as_scores()` filtering. Blog post on deferred errors referenced in issue. Only 1 comment from maintainer (\"I like this idea\").\n     8→\n     9→## Test Specifications\n    10→\n    11→**Designed**: 2026-02-13\n    12→**Test file**: `tests/testthat/test-score.R` (existing)\n    13→**Testing patterns observed**: testthat with data.table fixtures; `setup.R` pre-computes `scores_*` objects from `example_*` datasets; `expect_warning()`, `expect_no_condition()`, `suppressWarnings()` used extensively; `run_safely()` and `apply_metrics()` are internal (`:::`) but tested directly\n    14→\n    15→### Test 1: test_that(\"apply_metrics() emits a single batched warning when multiple metrics fail\", { ... })\n    16→\n    17→**Reproduces**: the core issue — currently each failed metric emits its own separate warning eagerly during the `lapply` loop\n    18→**Setup**:\n    19→- Create a `data.table` with a single column `x = 1:10`\n    20→- Define two metrics that always error:\n    21→  - `fail1 = function(x) stop(\"error in fail1\")`\n    22→  - `fail2 = function(x) stop(\"error in fail2\")`\n    23→- Also include one metric that succeeds: `good = function(x) x + 1`\n    24→- Pass as `metrics = list(\"fail1\" = fail1, \"good\" = good, \"fail2\" = fail2)`\n    25→**Action**:\n    26→- Call `scoringutils:::apply_metrics(forecast = dt, metrics = metrics, dt$x)`\n    27→**Expected**:\n    28→- Exactly ONE warning is emitted (not two separate warnings)\n    29→- The single warning message mentions both `fail1` and `fail2` metric names and their respective error messages\n    30→- The successful metric `good` column is still computed and present in the output data.table\n    31→- The failed metric columns (`fail1`, `fail2`) are NOT present as columns in the output\n    32→**Fails now because**:\n    33→- `run_safely()` calls `cli_warn()` immediately on each failure inside the `lapply` loop, producing two separate warnings instead of one batched warning\n    34→\n    35→### Test 2: test_that(\"apply_metrics() emits no warning when all metrics succeed\", { ... })\n    36→\n    37→**Reproduces**: regression guard — ensures batching logic doesn't introduce spurious warnings when nothing fails\n    38→**Setup**:\n    39→- Create a `data.table` with column `x = 1:10`\n    40→- Define two succeeding metrics: `m1 = function(x) x + 1`, `m2 = function(x) x * 2`\n    41→**Action**:\n    42→- Call `scoringutils:::apply_metrics(forecast = dt, metrics = list(\"m1\" = m1, \"m2\" = m2), dt$x)`\n    43→**Expected**:\n    44→- `expect_no_condition()` — no warning, message, or error is emitted\n    45→- Both metric columns are present and have correct values\n    46→**Fails now because**:\n    47→- This test should PASS on both current and fixed code (regression guard)\n    48→\n    49→### Test 3: test_that(\"score() emits a single batched warning when a metric fails\", { ... })\n    50→\n    51→**Reproduces**: the user-facing manifestation of the bug via the public `score()` API\n    52→**Setup**:\n    53→- Use `example_sample_continuous` with only 1 sample (i.e., filter to `sample_id == 20` after `na.omit()`)\n    54→- This causes `log