{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018BQXJFQ7cfwWnqYPAP4gHf","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→#' @title Evaluate forecasts\n     2→#' @description `score()` applies a selection of scoring metrics to a forecast\n     3→#' object.\n     4→#' `score()` is a generic that dispatches to different methods depending on the\n     5→#' class of the input data.\n     6→#'\n     7→#' See [as_forecast_binary()], [as_forecast_quantile()] etc. for information on\n     8→#' how to create a forecast object.\n     9→#'\n    10→#' See [get_forecast_unit()] for more information on the concept of a forecast\n    11→#' unit.\n    12→#'\n    13→#' For additional help and examples, check out the paper\n    14→#' [Evaluating Forecasts with scoringutils in\n    15→#' R](https://arxiv.org/abs/2205.07090).\n    16→#' @param forecast A forecast object (a validated data.table with predicted and\n    17→#'   observed values).\n    18→#' @param metrics A named list of scoring functions. Each element should be a\n    19→#'   function reference, not a function call. For example, use\n    20→#'   `list(\"crps\" = crps_sample)` rather than `list(\"crps\" = crps_sample())`.\n    21→#'   Names will be used as column names in the output. See [get_metrics()] for\n    22→#'   more information on the default metrics used. See the *Customising metrics*\n    23→#'   section below for information on how to pass custom arguments to scoring\n    24→#'   functions.\n    25→#' @param ... Currently unused. You *cannot* pass additional arguments to scoring\n    26→#'   functions via `...`. See the *Customising metrics* section below for\n    27→#'   details on how to use [purrr::partial()] to pass arguments to individual\n    28→#'   metrics.\n    29→#' @details\n    30→#' **Customising metrics**\n    31→#'\n    32→#' If you want to pass arguments to a scoring function, you need change the\n    33→#' scoring function itself via e.g. [purrr::partial()] and pass an updated list\n    34→#' of functions with your custom metric to the `metrics` argument in `score()`.\n    35→#' For example, to use [interval_coverage()] with `interval_range = 90`, you\n    36→#' would define a new function, e.g.\n    37→#' `interval_coverage_90 <- purrr::partial(interval_coverage, interval_range = 90)`\n    38→#' and pass this new function to `metrics` in `score()`.\n    39→#'\n    40→#' Note that if you want to pass a variable as an argument, you can\n    41→#' unquote it with `!!` to make sure the value is evaluated only once when the\n    42→#' function is created. Consider the following example:\n    43→#' ```\n    44→#' custom_arg <- \"foo\"\n    45→#' print1 <- purrr::partial(print, x = custom_arg)\n    46→#' print2 <- purrr::partial(print, x = !!custom_arg)\n    47→#'\n    48→#' custom_arg <- \"bar\"\n    49→#' print1() # prints 'bar'\n    50→#' print2() # prints 'foo'\n    51→#' ```\n    52→#'\n    53→#' @return\n    54→#' An object of class `scores`. This object is a data.table with\n    55→#' unsummarised scores (one score per forecast) and has an additional attribute\n    56→#' `metrics` with the names of the metrics used for scoring. See\n    57→#' [summarise_scores()]) for information on how to summarise\n    58→#' scores.\n    59→#' @importFrom data.table ':=' as.data.table\n    60→#' @importFrom stats na.omit\n    61→#' @keywords scoring\n    62→#' @examples\n    63→#' \\dontshow{\n    64→#'   data.table::setDTthreads(2) # restricts number of cores used on CRAN\n    65→#' }\n    66→#'\n    67→#' validated <- as_forecast_quantile(example_quantile)\n    68→#' score(validated) |>\n    69→#'   summarise_scores(by = c(\"model\", \"target_type\"))\n    70→#'\n    71→#' # set forecast unit manually (to avoid issues with scoringutils trying to\n    72→#' # determine the forecast unit automatically)\n    73→#' example_quantile |>\n    74→#'   as_forecast_quantile(\n    75→#'     forecast_unit = c(\n    76→#'       \"location\", \"target_end_date\", \"target_type\", \"horizon\", \"model\"\n    77→#'     )\n    78→#'   ) |>\n    79→#'   score()\n    80→#'\n    81→#' # forecast formats with different metrics\n    82→#' \\dontrun{\n    83→#' score(as_forecast_binary(example_binary))\n    84→#' score(as_forecast_quantile(example_quantile))\n    85→#' score(as_forecast_point(example_point))\n    86→#' score(as_forecast_sample(example_sample_discrete))\n    87→#' score(as_forecast_sample(example_sample_continuous))\n    88→#' }\n    89→#'\n    90→#' # passing a subset of metrics using select_metrics()\n    91→#' # (the preferred approach for selecting from default metrics)\n    92→#' example_sample_continuous |>\n    93→#'   as_forecast_sample() |>\n    94→#'   score(metrics = select_metrics(\n    95→#'     get_metrics(as_forecast_sample(example_sample_continuous)),\n    96→#'     select = c(\"crps\", \"mad\")\n    97→#'   ))\n    98→#'\n    99→#' # passing a custom list of metrics manually\n   100→#' # make sure to pass the function itself, not the result of calling it,\n   101→#' # i.e. use `crps_sample` (correct) instead of `crps_sample()` (incorrect)\n   102→#' example_sample_continuous |>\n   103→#'   as_forecast_sample() |>\n   104→#'   score(metrics = list(\"crps\" = crps_sample, \"mad\" = mad_sample))\n   105→#'\n   106→#' # multivariate forecasts\n   107→#' \\dontrun{\n   108→#' score(example_multivariate_sample)\n   109→#' }\n   110→#'\n   111→#' @author Nikos Bosse \\email{nikosbosse@@gmail.com}\n   112→#' @references\n   113→#' Bosse NI, Gruson H, Cori A, van Leeuwen E, Funk S, Abbott S\n   114→#' (2022) Evaluating Forecasts with scoringutils in R.\n   115→#' \\doi{10.48550/arXiv.2205.07090}\n   116→#' @export\n   117→\n   118→score <- function(forecast, metrics, ...) {\n   119→  UseMethod(\"score\")\n   120→}\n   121→\n   122→#' @importFrom cli cli_abort\n   123→#' @export\n   124→score.default <- function(forecast, metrics, ...) {\n   125→  cli_abort(\n   126→    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n   127→    c(\n   128→      \"!\" = \"The input needs to be a valid forecast object.\",\n   129→      \"i\" = \"Please convert to a `forecast` object first by calling the\n   130→      appropriate {.fn as_forecast_<type>} function).\"\n   131→    )\n   132→    #nolint end\n   133→  )\n   134→}\n   135→\n   136→\n   137→#' @title Apply a list of functions to a data table of forecasts\n   138→#' @description\n   139→#' This helper function applies scoring rules (stored as a list of\n   140→#' functions) to a data table of forecasts. `apply_metrics` is used within\n   141→#' `score()` to apply all scoring rules to the data.\n   142→#' Scoring rules are wrapped in [run_safely()] to catch errors and to make\n   143→#' sure that only arguments are passed to the scoring rule that are actually\n   144→#' accepted by it.\n   145→#' @param ... Additional arguments to be passed to the scoring rules. Note that\n   146→#'   this is currently not used, as all calls to `apply_scores` currently\n   147→#'   avoid passing arguments via `...` and instead expect that the metrics\n   148→#'   directly be modified using [purrr::partial()].\n   149→#' @inheritParams score\n   150→#' @returns A data table with the forecasts and the calculated metrics.\n   151→#' @keywords internal\n   152→apply_metrics <- function(forecast, metrics, ...) {\n   153→  lapply(names(metrics), function(metric_name) {\n   154→    result <- do.call(\n   155→      run_safely,\n   156→      list(..., fun = metrics[[metric_name]], metric_name = metric_name)\n   157→    )\n   158→    if (!is.null(result)) {\n   159→      forecast[, (metric_name) := result]\n   160→    }\n   161→  })\n   162→  return(forecast)\n   163→}\n   164→\n   165→\n   166→#' @title Run a function safely\n   167→#' @description\n   168→#' This is a wrapper/helper function designed to run a function safely\n   169→#' when it is not completely clear what arguments could be passed to the\n   170→#' function.\n   171→#'\n   172→#' All named arguments in `...` that are not accepted by `fun` are removed.\n   173→#' All unnamed arguments are passed on to the function. In case `fun` errors,\n   174→#' the error will be converted to a warning and `run_safely` returns `NULL`.\n   175→#'\n   176→#' `run_safely` can be useful when constructing functions to be used as\n   177→#' metrics in [score()].\n   178→#'\n   179→#' @param ... Arguments to pass to `fun`.\n   180→#' @param fun A function to execute.\n   181→#' @param metric_name A character string with the name of the metric. Used to\n   182→#'   provide a more informative warning message in case `fun` errors.\n   183→#' @importFrom cli cli_warn\n   184→#' @importFrom checkmate assert_function\n   185→#' @returns The result of `fun` or `NULL` if `fun` errors\n   186→#' @keywords internal\n   187→#' @examples\n   188→#' f <- function(x) {x}\n   189→#' scoringutils:::run_safely(2, fun = f, metric_name = \"f\")\n   190→#' scoringutils:::run_safely(2, y = 3, fun = f, metric_name = \"f\")\n   191→#' scoringutils:::run_safely(fun = f, metric_name = \"f\")\n   192→#' scoringutils:::run_safely(y = 3, fun = f, metric_name = \"f\")\n   193→run_safely <- function(..., fun, metric_name) {\n   194→  assert_function(fun)\n   195→  args <- list(...)\n   196→  possible_args <- names(formals(fun))\n   197→\n   198→  # Check if the function accepts ... as an argument\n   199→  if (\"...\" %in% possible_args) {\n   200→    valid_args <- args\n   201→  } else if (is.null(names(args))) {\n   202→    # if no arguments are named, just pass all arguments on\n   203→    valid_args <- args\n   204→  } else {\n   205→    # keep valid arguments as well as unnamed arguments\n   206→    valid_args <- args[!nzchar(names(args)) | names(args) %in% possible_args]\n   207→  }\n   208→\n   209→  result <- try(do.call(fun, valid_args), silent = TRUE)\n   210→\n   211→  if (inherits(result, \"try-error\")) {\n   212→    #nolint start: object_usage_linter\n   213→    msg <- conditionMessage(attr(result, \"condition\"))\n   214→    cli_warn(\n   215→      c(\n   216→        \"!\" = \"Computation for {.var {metric_name}} failed.\n   217→        Error: {msg}.\"\n   218→      )\n   219→    )\n   220→    #nolint end\n   221→    return(NULL)\n   222→  }\n   223→  return(result)\n   224→}\n   225→\n   226→\n   227→#' @title Validate metrics\n   228→#'\n   229→#' @description\n   230→#' This function validates whether the list of metrics is a list\n   231→#' of valid functions.\n   232→#'\n   233→#' The function is used in [score()] to make sure that all metrics are valid\n   234→#' functions.\n   235→#'\n   236→#' @param metrics A named list with metrics. Every element should be a scoring\n   237→#'   function to be applied to the data.\n   238→#' @importFrom cli cli_warn\n   239→#'\n   240→#' @return\n   241→#' A named list of metrics, with those filtered out that are not\n   242→#' valid functions\n   243→#' @importFrom checkmate assert_list test_list check_function\n   244→#' @keywords internal_input_check\n   245→validate_metrics <- function(metrics) {\n   246→\n   247→  assert_list(metrics, min.len = 1, names = \"named\")\n   248→\n   249→  for (i in seq_along(metrics)) {\n   250→    check_fun <- check_function(metrics[[i]])\n   251→    if (!isTRUE(check_fun)) {\n   252→      #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n   253→      cli_warn(\n   254→        c(\n   255→          \"!\" = \"`Metrics` element number {i} is not a valid function.\"\n   256→        )\n   257→      )\n   258→      #nolint end\n   259→      names(metrics)[i] <- \"scoringutils_delete\"\n   260→    }\n   261→  }\n   262→  metrics[names(metrics) == \"scoringutils_delete\"] <- NULL\n   263→\n   264→  assert_list(metrics, min.len = 1, .var.name = \"valid metrics\")\n   265→\n   266→  return(metrics)\n   267→}\n   268→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"123bf52f-ba83-498c-9d18-f699e4c3227f","uuid":"8b8e2768-35cd-479b-a5c2-da70d7e343e1","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/nikos/github-synced/scoringutils-pipeline/R/score.R","content":"#' @title Evaluate forecasts\n#' @description `score()` applies a selection of scoring metrics to a forecast\n#' object.\n#' `score()` is a generic that dispatches to different methods depending on the\n#' class of the input data.\n#'\n#' See [as_forecast_binary()], [as_forecast_quantile()] etc. for information on\n#' how to create a forecast object.\n#'\n#' See [get_forecast_unit()] for more information on the concept of a forecast\n#' unit.\n#'\n#' For additional help and examples, check out the paper\n#' [Evaluating Forecasts with scoringutils in\n#' R](https://arxiv.org/abs/2205.07090).\n#' @param forecast A forecast object (a validated data.table with predicted and\n#'   observed values).\n#' @param metrics A named list of scoring functions. Each element should be a\n#'   function reference, not a function call. For example, use\n#'   `list(\"crps\" = crps_sample)` rather than `list(\"crps\" = crps_sample())`.\n#'   Names will be used as column names in the output. See [get_metrics()] for\n#'   more information on the default metrics used. See the *Customising metrics*\n#'   section below for information on how to pass custom arguments to scoring\n#'   functions.\n#' @param ... Currently unused. You *cannot* pass additional arguments to scoring\n#'   functions via `...`. See the *Customising metrics* section below for\n#'   details on how to use [purrr::partial()] to pass arguments to individual\n#'   metrics.\n#' @details\n#' **Customising metrics**\n#'\n#' If you want to pass arguments to a scoring function, you need change the\n#' scoring function itself via e.g. [purrr::partial()] and pass an updated list\n#' of functions with your custom metric to the `metrics` argument in `score()`.\n#' For example, to use [interval_coverage()] with `interval_range = 90`, you\n#' would define a new function, e.g.\n#' `interval_coverage_90 <- purrr::partial(interval_coverage, interval_range = 90)`\n#' and pass this new function to `metrics` in `score()`.\n#'\n#' Note that if you want to pass a variable as an argument, you can\n#' unquote it with `!!` to make sure the value is evaluated only once when the\n#' function is created. Consider the following example:\n#' ```\n#' custom_arg <- \"foo\"\n#' print1 <- purrr::partial(print, x = custom_arg)\n#' print2 <- purrr::partial(print, x = !!custom_arg)\n#'\n#' custom_arg <- \"bar\"\n#' print1() # prints 'bar'\n#' print2() # prints 'foo'\n#' ```\n#'\n#' @return\n#' An object of class `scores`. This object is a data.table with\n#' unsummarised scores (one score per forecast) and has an additional attribute\n#' `metrics` with the names of the metrics used for scoring. See\n#' [summarise_scores()]) for information on how to summarise\n#' scores.\n#' @importFrom data.table ':=' as.data.table\n#' @importFrom stats na.omit\n#' @keywords scoring\n#' @examples\n#' \\dontshow{\n#'   data.table::setDTthreads(2) # restricts number of cores used on CRAN\n#' }\n#'\n#' validated <- as_forecast_quantile(example_quantile)\n#' score(validated) |>\n#'   summarise_scores(by = c(\"model\", \"target_type\"))\n#'\n#' # set forecast unit manually (to avoid issues with scoringutils trying to\n#' # determine the forecast unit automatically)\n#' example_quantile |>\n#'   as_forecast_quantile(\n#'     forecast_unit = c(\n#'       \"location\", \"target_end_date\", \"target_type\", \"horizon\", \"model\"\n#'     )\n#'   ) |>\n#'   score()\n#'\n#' # forecast formats with different metrics\n#' \\dontrun{\n#' score(as_forecast_binary(example_binary))\n#' score(as_forecast_quantile(example_quantile))\n#' score(as_forecast_point(example_point))\n#' score(as_forecast_sample(example_sample_discrete))\n#' score(as_forecast_sample(example_sample_continuous))\n#' }\n#'\n#' # passing a subset of metrics using select_metrics()\n#' # (the preferred approach for selecting from default metrics)\n#' example_sample_continuous |>\n#'   as_forecast_sample() |>\n#'   score(metrics = select_metrics(\n#'     get_metrics(as_forecast_sample(example_sample_continuous)),\n#'     select = c(\"crps\", \"mad\")\n#'   ))\n#'\n#' # passing a custom list of metrics manually\n#' # make sure to pass the function itself, not the result of calling it,\n#' # i.e. use `crps_sample` (correct) instead of `crps_sample()` (incorrect)\n#' example_sample_continuous |>\n#'   as_forecast_sample() |>\n#'   score(metrics = list(\"crps\" = crps_sample, \"mad\" = mad_sample))\n#'\n#' # multivariate forecasts\n#' \\dontrun{\n#' score(example_multivariate_sample)\n#' }\n#'\n#' @author Nikos Bosse \\email{nikosbosse@@gmail.com}\n#' @references\n#' Bosse NI, Gruson H, Cori A, van Leeuwen E, Funk S, Abbott S\n#' (2022) Evaluating Forecasts with scoringutils in R.\n#' \\doi{10.48550/arXiv.2205.07090}\n#' @export\n\nscore <- function(forecast, metrics, ...) {\n  UseMethod(\"score\")\n}\n\n#' @importFrom cli cli_abort\n#' @export\nscore.default <- function(forecast, metrics, ...) {\n  cli_abort(\n    #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n    c(\n      \"!\" = \"The input needs to be a valid forecast object.\",\n      \"i\" = \"Please convert to a `forecast` object first by calling the\n      appropriate {.fn as_forecast_<type>} function).\"\n    )\n    #nolint end\n  )\n}\n\n\n#' @title Apply a list of functions to a data table of forecasts\n#' @description\n#' This helper function applies scoring rules (stored as a list of\n#' functions) to a data table of forecasts. `apply_metrics` is used within\n#' `score()` to apply all scoring rules to the data.\n#' Scoring rules are wrapped in [run_safely()] to catch errors and to make\n#' sure that only arguments are passed to the scoring rule that are actually\n#' accepted by it.\n#' @param ... Additional arguments to be passed to the scoring rules. Note that\n#'   this is currently not used, as all calls to `apply_scores` currently\n#'   avoid passing arguments via `...` and instead expect that the metrics\n#'   directly be modified using [purrr::partial()].\n#' @inheritParams score\n#' @returns A data table with the forecasts and the calculated metrics.\n#' @keywords internal\napply_metrics <- function(forecast, metrics, ...) {\n  lapply(names(metrics), function(metric_name) {\n    result <- do.call(\n      run_safely,\n      list(..., fun = metrics[[metric_name]], metric_name = metric_name)\n    )\n    if (!is.null(result)) {\n      forecast[, (metric_name) := result]\n    }\n  })\n  return(forecast)\n}\n\n\n#' @title Run a function safely\n#' @description\n#' This is a wrapper/helper function designed to run a function safely\n#' when it is not completely clear what arguments could be passed to the\n#' function.\n#'\n#' All named arguments in `...` that are not accepted by `fun` are removed.\n#' All unnamed arguments are passed on to the function. In case `fun` errors,\n#' the error will be converted to a warning and `run_safely` returns `NULL`.\n#'\n#' `run_safely` can be useful when constructing functions to be used as\n#' metrics in [score()].\n#'\n#' @param ... Arguments to pass to `fun`.\n#' @param fun A function to execute.\n#' @param metric_name A character string with the name of the metric. Used to\n#'   provide a more informative warning message in case `fun` errors.\n#' @importFrom cli cli_warn\n#' @importFrom checkmate assert_function\n#' @returns The result of `fun` or `NULL` if `fun` errors\n#' @keywords internal\n#' @examples\n#' f <- function(x) {x}\n#' scoringutils:::run_safely(2, fun = f, metric_name = \"f\")\n#' scoringutils:::run_safely(2, y = 3, fun = f, metric_name = \"f\")\n#' scoringutils:::run_safely(fun = f, metric_name = \"f\")\n#' scoringutils:::run_safely(y = 3, fun = f, metric_name = \"f\")\nrun_safely <- function(..., fun, metric_name) {\n  assert_function(fun)\n  args <- list(...)\n  possible_args <- names(formals(fun))\n\n  # Check if the function accepts ... as an argument\n  if (\"...\" %in% possible_args) {\n    valid_args <- args\n  } else if (is.null(names(args))) {\n    # if no arguments are named, just pass all arguments on\n    valid_args <- args\n  } else {\n    # keep valid arguments as well as unnamed arguments\n    valid_args <- args[!nzchar(names(args)) | names(args) %in% possible_args]\n  }\n\n  result <- try(do.call(fun, valid_args), silent = TRUE)\n\n  if (inherits(result, \"try-error\")) {\n    #nolint start: object_usage_linter\n    msg <- conditionMessage(attr(result, \"condition\"))\n    cli_warn(\n      c(\n        \"!\" = \"Computation for {.var {metric_name}} failed.\n        Error: {msg}.\"\n      )\n    )\n    #nolint end\n    return(NULL)\n  }\n  return(result)\n}\n\n\n#' @title Validate metrics\n#'\n#' @description\n#' This function validates whether the list of metrics is a list\n#' of valid functions.\n#'\n#' The function is used in [score()] to make sure that all metrics are valid\n#' functions.\n#'\n#' @param metrics A named list with metrics. Every element should be a scoring\n#'   function to be applied to the data.\n#' @importFrom cli cli_warn\n#'\n#' @return\n#' A named list of metrics, with those filtered out that are not\n#' valid functions\n#' @importFrom checkmate assert_list test_list check_function\n#' @keywords internal_input_check\nvalidate_metrics <- function(metrics) {\n\n  assert_list(metrics, min.len = 1, names = \"named\")\n\n  for (i in seq_along(metrics)) {\n    check_fun <- check_function(metrics[[i]])\n    if (!isTRUE(check_fun)) {\n      #nolint start: keyword_quote_linter\n      cli_warn(\n        c(\n          \"!\" = \"`Metrics` element number {i} is not a valid function.\"\n        )\n      )\n      #nolint end\n      names(metrics)[i] <- \"scoringutils_delete\"\n    }\n  }\n  metrics[names(metrics) == \"scoringutils_delete\"] <- NULL\n\n  assert_list(metrics, min.len = 1, .var.name = \"valid metrics\")\n\n  return(metrics)\n}\n","numLines":268,"startLine":1,"totalLines":268}}}
